      PlayMED ist MAILWARE, d.h. es ist FREEWARE mit der Beschränkung, dass
      jeder, der es benutzt, mir eine eMail schicken muss (bitte!).
      
      Sämtliche Rechte liegen beim Autor dieses Programms: Robin Schmidt.
      
      Der Autor übernimmt keinerlei Verantwortung für eventuelle Schäden, die
      durch die Benutzung dieses Programms entstehen.

      Diese Dokumentation erhebt keinen Anspruch auf Vollständigkeit oder
      Korrektheit.
      
      PlayMED darf gerne weitergegeben werden, solange dabei
                1. weniger als DM2,- für das Programm verlangt wird
                2. dieses Guide-File beiliegt
                3. kein Geld für das Guide-File verlangt wird(!)
                4. PlayMED und PlayMED.guide in unveränderter Form
                   weitergegeben werden (packen erlaubt).
      
      medplayer.library, octaplayer.library und octamixplayer.library sind
      © RBF Software (© Teijo Kinnunen und Ray Burt-Frost)
      
      Wer immer diese Programm benutzt, schicke mir bitte eine eMail an
      folgende Adresse:
      
                     aaa-soft@gmx.net

      
@ENDNODE

@NODE "aaag" "A A A - Software"


                   @{b}Absolutio Artis Aeternalis      Software@{ub}
                (Die Vollendung der ewigen Kunst)

          A A A Software ist eine Gemeinschaft aus Hobbyprogrammierern mit
          derzeit einem Mitglied.
          
          Wir haben uns vorgenommen, qualitativ hochwertige Software zu
          produzieren, sowohl hochwertig vom Programm her, wie auch von
          Benutzerfreundlichkeit, Grafik, Sound und Story.
          
          Derzeit laufen zwei Projekte:
          
          Das beste Fantasy-RPG aller Zeiten: FREIHEIT!
          
          und
          
          die Umsetzung des C64 Klassikers Mafia-Games.
          
          Zur Vollendung dieser beiden Projekte unter den oben genannten
          Richtlinien werden noch Hobbyprogrammierer und -grafiker gesucht.
          
          Diese sollten eine oder mehrere der folgenden Fähigkeiten
          besitzen:

										Grafiker
										3d-Programmierung   (Grafik-Engine wie bei z.B. Trapped oder DOOM)
										objektorientiertes Programmieren
										künstliche Intelligenz
										Videosequenzen aufnehmen, einspeisen und einbinden
										evtl. Musiker (nur als zusätzliche Qualifikation)


          Meldungen und Kommentare oder was auch immer an
          
                    aaa-soft@gmx.net


          A A A - Software besteht aus:    @{" Robin Schmidt " LINK "RSg"}


@ENDNODE

@NODE "RSg" "A A A - Mitglieder:   Robin Schmidt"


         Robin Schmidt, geb. 08. Sep. 1980 in Berlin/Deutschland
         
         Seit 1982 wohnhaft in Neumünster/Deutschland, besuche dort derzeit
         die Klaus-Groth-Schule im 13. Jahrgang, wo ich am 24. Juli 2000
         mein Abschluss-Zeugnis (Abitur) erhalten werde.
         
         Dann werde ich nach Ulm a. d. Donau/Deutschland ziehen, um dort
         ein Jahr Zivildienst (Alternative zum Wehrdienst) abzuleisten und
         dann an der dortigen Universität Wirtschaftsmathematik zu studieren.
         
         Ich programmiere seit ich sechs oder sieben Jahre alt bin. Angefangen
         habe ich auf dem C64 meines großen Bruders, indem ich Beispielpro-
         gramme aus den Handbüchern abgetippt und variiert habe. Kurze Zeit
         später hatte ich selbst einen C64 und arbeitete dort kräftig an
         eigenen kleinen Projekten. Da BASIC auf dem C64 sehr langsam war,
         versuchte ich es mit Assambler, muss aber zugeben, dass ich dazu
         damals noch zu blöd war: Ich hab es gerade mal geschafft, mit viel
         Aufwand und zwei Stunden Arbeit ein 'Hello world' auf den Bildschirm
         zu bekommen, eine Sache, für die man in Basic fünf Sekunden braucht.
         Dann kam 1990 der Amiga500 ins Haus. AmigaBASIC war leistungsfähig
         und schnell (verglichen mit dem C64-Basic), ich machte meine Fort-
         schritte. Als dann aber auch AmigaBasic zu langsam war, besorgte
         ich mir einen ordentlichen Kompiler: MaxonBASIC.
           Zusammen mit meinem neuen A1200 (wir befinden uns im Jahre 1993),
         machten wir dem Betriebssystem schwer zu schaffen. Leider ist die
         Dokumentation der deutschen Hi-Soft-Variante sehr schlecht (um es
         mal euphemistisch auszudrücken), so dass ich die volle Leistungs-
         fähigkeit des Systems erst durch Steffen L. kennenlernte,
         der mir bei einigen Problemen mit der Benutzung von Betriebsystem-
         bibliothensfunktionen sehr half. Leider brach mein Kontakt zu Steffen
         ab aus Gründen, die er mir nie wirklich nennen wollte oder konnte,
         so dass ich mich nur langsam durch das, was ich mir selbst erarbeite,
         denn gute Literatur ist einfach zu teuer für mich, fortentwickel.
         Aber durch seine Hilfe nahm in mir ein Traum Gestalt an, den ich
         eines Tages erfüllen werde: Ein Fantasy-RPG der Superlative.
           Bevor der Kontakt zu ihm abbrach, planten wir gemeinsam dieses
         Spiel zu machen, und ich schuf eine fantastische Welt in der
         Meinung, dass eine Story nur dann gut sein kann, wenn der Hintergrund
         lückenlos stimmig ist, wenn die Welt gewachsen ist. Diese Welt
         existiert nun in mir, und eines Tages werde ich aus ihr Wirklichkeit
         werden lassen. Leider sind unsere Pläne so ausgereift gewesen, dass
         meine Fähigkeiten als Programmierer nicht ansatzweise ausreichen,
         das Projekt umzusetzen. Steffen hätte es vielleicht geschafft, doch
         er ist weg. Kennst Du nicht jemanden, der fähig und willens wäre,
         das beste RPG dieser Zeit zu machen? Sag Bescheid! Privat bin ich
         zu erreichen unter
         
                     RobNS@gmx.net


@ENDNODE

@NODE "MedPlaysg" "PlayMED spielt"


          PlayMED V1 spielt alle MED-Module der Generationen MMD0 und MMD1
          mit vier Kanälen und Samples unter 137000 Bytes Größe.
          
          PlayMED V2 ebenso
          
          PlayMED V3 wie V1, zusatzlich Module der Generationen bis MMD3
          mit Mix-Routine für 1-64 Kanäle oder Mix-Routine für 5-8 Kanäle.
          Also alle MED-Module, die mit dem OctaMED SoundStudion V1.03c
          oder früheren Versionen erstellt werden können.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "English" "Contents"


      Welcome to the @{b}PlayMED@{ub}-Guide-File !

      @{" What is it ? " LINK "intre"}       a short introduction

      @{" It's alive ! " LINK "reqe"}       how to make PlayMED work (or: requirements)

      @{" usage        " LINK "usee"}       it's as easy as possible (nearly)

      @{" history      " LINK "histe"}       how this prog got what it is

      @{" programme    " LINK "proe"}       for the developers among you

      @{" disclaimer   " LINK "dise"}       it's neccessary

      @{" AAA-Software " LINK "aaae"}       something for myself


@ENDNODE

@NODE "intre" "Introduction"


      Well, PlayMED is a programme to randomly choose a MED-module and play
      it, until the user presses a button (which in fact is no button but
      a simple image). Then a new mod will be chosen randomly, and so on...
      It's really useful if you 1. don't like to click through several
      sub-directories and 2. can't/don't like to choose the mod you want
      to hear by your own.

      Since version 3 there are some additional functions which e.g. make it
      possible to choose a module by our own or automatically choose a new
      mod after a set time.
      
      PlayMED is as user-friendly as possible, since I myself use it. I hope
      you find working with it as comfortable as I do.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "reqe" "Requirements"


      PlayMED needs the following things to run:

           - an @{b}Amiga@{ub}  (hey, the good, old joke...)
           - @{b}PlayMED@{ub}   (and another one just following!)
           - @{b}medplayer.library@{ub}; @{b}octaplayer.library@{ub};
             @{b}octamixplayer.library@{ub}
             You should get them via Aminet. Or you can get them from me.
             (s. @{" AAA-Software " LINK "aaae"}); PlayMED V2< needs medplayer.library only
           - @{b}asl.library@{ub} Everyone has this!?
           - some @{b}MED-modules@{ub} you find them everywhere (Aminet)
           - @{b}Kick 3.1@{ub} Maybe PlayMED runs with earlier versions of
             kickstart. It should run with @{b}Kick 2.0@{ub}, but it's not
             been tested.
             Careful: PlayMED does not check the library-versions to make
             it possible for everyone to check whether it runs or not.
             Please report me!
           - the CLI-command DIR in your C: dir
           - The graphics are made for a 640x512 workbench. It's possible
             to run PlayMED with other resolution but may look queer. THIS
             WILL BE FIXED @{i}ASAP@{ui} (see at @{" future " LINK "futue"}).


      Okay: You've already decrunched PlayMED and put it somewhere on your
      harddisk. It will run in any directory and doesn't need any 'assign'.

@{b}      Attention: Do never delete the icon ! Even when you don't need it@{ub}
      (that's for the CLI-only users). PlayMED keeps on working, but you
      reduce my fantastic prog to a simple player-programme like there are
      thousend others. PlayMED saves important information in the tool-types.

      More detailed: The tool-types of PlayMED should look like this:

                 WINX=0                             X-position of the window
                 WINY=20                            Y-position
                 DEFMOD=Work:Song                   name of the module, that
                                                    shall be loaded immediately
                                                    after start
                 DIRNUMBER=2                        number of dirs that contain
                                                    your modules
                 DIR1=Work:Music/Modules            You should name as many paths
                 DIR2=Work:Music/selfmade           as DIRNUMBER says there are.
                 OUTTIME=0200                       Preferences for the
                                                    @{" TIMEOUT-requester " LINK "TimeOute"}
                 REQDIR=Work:Music/Modules          This is where the file-req
                 REQPATTERN=~(#?.(info|backdrop))   leads you to choose a file
                 REQX=58                            that fits the @{" pattern " LINK "Mustere"}
                 REQY=32                            after it's opened its
                 REQW=341                           window at the given
                 REQH=461                           XY-position with the
                                                    given size.
      
      At the moment really important are
      
      DEFMOD        When there is a mod you'd like to here everytime you
                    start PlayMED, you should name its path and name here.
                    This parameter is optional.
      DIRNUMBER     To my real shame I couldn't find a way to count
                    tool-types. Therefore you have to set the number
                    of directories which are to be searched for modules
                    by setting this tool-type.
      DIRx          This is the place where you have to name the paths PlayMED
                    should use to find some playable mods. You replace the
                    'x' by some number (1, 2, 3, ...) as shown in the example.
                    There is no maximum number of dirs set (not by me at least...).

                    If DIRNUMBER is higher than the number of really named
                    DIRx's, there is a small loss of time, but no real
                    problem(=GURU).
                    Should DIRNUMBER be smaller than the number of really named
                    DIRx's, PlayMED does only read DIRNUMBER DIRs !
                    So don't ask why some of your mods are never played...

      Now, that all this is correctly initialised, we can start with the
      real stuff ! 8-)


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Mustere" "DOS patterns"


      Alas the DOS patterns are not explained in the standard Amiga
      documentation. Therefore I'll explain the most important ones.
      
      Sign      Explaination
         ?      stands for one character
                  A?B   fits e.g.   AAB, AaB, AcB, A1
                        but not     AABB, AcdB
         #      repeat the following sign
                  A#B   fits e.g.   A, ABBBBBBBB, AbbbbBbBbBB
                  A#BC  fits e.g.   AC, ABC, ABbBbBbC
                  A#?   fits all words that beginn with A
                  A#?B  fits e.g.   AB, AanythingB, AXY12345RERERB
                  #?.txt  fits all names that end with .txt
         ()     make a unit
                  A#(BC) fits e.g.   A, ABC, ABCbcbcbcBC
         |      OR-operator
                  A(B|C) fits   AB   and   AC
                  A#(B|C)D fits e.g.AD, ABD, ACD, ABBD, ACCD, ABCD, ACBD
         %      stands for NOTHING
                 (A|%)B  fits  AB  and  B
                 A(B|%)#C  fits e.g.A, AB, ABC, AC, ACC, ABCCCCCC
         '      use the following sign as a simple sign
                 A'?   fits         A?
                 A#('?)  fits e.g.  A, A?, A???????????
         ~      negation of the following pattern
                 ~A#?   fits all words that do not beginn with A
                 ~(#?.info)  fits all word that do not end with .info
                 ~(#?.(info|backdrop)) excludes all .info and .backdrop files


@ENDNODE

@NODE "usee" "Usage"


      Now: Start PlayMED from Workbench or CLI or how ever you want.

      Maybe the sound-channels are free (you do not run MaxonMAGIC
      or SoundTracker, etc.). Then this should happen:
      
      A window appears. A button named PlayNEXT fills all the window.
      A close-gadget, a forward-/backward-gadget, nothing else.
      The text of the WB's screen's title changes!
      If the preferences in the tool-types are correct (-> @{" Requirements " LINK "reqe"}),
      your comp should play a module now. If not, it doesn't matter for the
      following things.

      You have these possibilities:
      
      LOAD A MODULE RANDOMLY: Click on 'PlayNEXT' or press [SPACE]. PlayMED
                              now tries to load a @{" playable " LINK "MedPlayse"} mod from the dirs
                              named in the tool-types. When a file isn't
                              playable, it's name is removed from the mod-list
                              and PlayMED does not try to load it again.
                              Instead a new file is loaded. It may be that
                              there is @{i}no@{ui} file left in the mod-list of PlayMED.
                              Then your only chance is to choose mods via
                              file-requester. Furthermore you should change
                              the tool-types, for the named directories did
                              not contain any playable MED-modules.
      LOAD ONE SPECIAL MODULE: Press the right mouse-button or [TAB] while
                               the PlayMED window is activ (indeed all actions
                               won't work with in-active window). A standard-
                               ASL-file-requester asks you to choose a module.
                               PlayMED tries to play this after it has been
                               chosen. You should hear any success. Nothing
                               happens, if the file was not playable.
                               Position, size, path and pattern of the FR
                               are save in the icon when you quit the prog.
      SET AND ACTIVATE TIMEOUT: Press [RETURN] to open the
                               @{" TIMEOUT-requester " LINK "TimeOute"}.
      UNSET TIMEOUT: If the timeout-function is activ, another push on [RETURN]
                     de-activates is.
            The status of the timeout-function is shown in the screen's title-bar.
      QUIT PROGRAMME: Click on the close-gadget or press [q], [Q] or [ESC].
                      This causes the programme to save any changes in position
                      of the main window, the parameters of the file-requester
                      and the OUTTIME in the tool-types. @{b}The TIMEOUT will only
                      be saved, when other things have been changed, too!@{ub}


@ENDNODE

@NODE "TimeOute" "TIMEOUT-requester"


  This is a window which seemingly just consists of a close-gadget,
  a forward-/backward-gadget and the text 'mmss' (and indeed there is nothing
  else!). In this window it's possible to set the time after which PlayMED
  automatically tries to open another module from the set directories.
  While you think about the time you want, you may still work with the main
  window like before (PlayMED creates a new task: be very very VERY proud...).
  The time consists of four digits: The first and second are the minutes
  and the third and fourth are the seconds (therefore: 'mmss'). Some examples
  should clear any understanding:
  
         You enter:                      This time is set:

         1234                            12 mins and 34 secs
         0012                                12 secs
         12[RETURN]                          12 secs
         123[RETURN]                      1 min and 23 secs
         [RETURN]                         recover the time set the time
                                          before (or the time set in the
                                          tool-types)
         [ESC] or close-gadget               none

         [q] and [Q] have the same meaning as [RETURN]
         and [c] and [C] the same meaning as [ESC].


@ENDNODE

@NODE "histe" "some history"


      Is there anybody really interested in this?
      I thought so, therefore I save some time and skip the translation of
      this part. Try the German text if you're really interested.
      Or mail me, then I will do my best.

      For some future stuff click @{" here " LINK "futue"}.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "futue" "future - visions - dreams - what's next?"


      I'm planning to include the following improvements in later versions:
      
             - optional: Use complete directory-trees with all sub-dirs.
               To save some time, I shall include search-patterns to
               exclude some mods (if you have a library of 1000 modules,
               PlayMED takes ages to start), or just let you set a max
               number of modules to load (optional). The consequence will
               be that I shan't read dirs via 'Execute Dir' but using a
               new, self-made routine.
             - optional: read the mod-list from an external file which the
               user may edit with some text-editor
               - For this purpose a programme will read specified dirs
                 and create a complete mod-list. This would decrease the
                 flexibility of PlayMED, for every new module has to be
                 included in the mod-list by hand (user). An advantage
                 would be the greater speed with great mod-libraries.
               - You might set priorities: Which mod do you want to hear
                 more often than others?
             - open the PlayMED-window on any PUBLIC-SCREEN
             - adapt to screen's size/scale graphics
             - everything you want me to include, as long as your
               suggestions are useful and possible.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "proe" "about the programme"


      This programme has been developed with MaxonBASIC (the German equivalent
      of HiSoft-basic (it's in fact 100% compatible, has the same GUI, the
      same compiler and the same debugger, but it has translated menus a.s.o.
      and a really MISERABLE (!!!SCREAM!!!) documentation) and uses the
      following system-libraries for the following aims:
      
          exec.library      organize memory, create second task, communication
                            between both tasks
           dos.library      call 'execute dir' in order to read directories,
                            'delay' to slow down the prog without wasting
                            CPU-time. PS: Do NEVER use 'delay' in a task...
     intuition.library      window-stuff, event-handling, mouse- and
                            keyboard-handling
           asl.library      file-requester
      graphics.library      'drawimage' PlayNEXT-image
     workbench.library  and
          icon.library      load/save tool-types
         medplayer.lib V7   load/play/free 4-channel-MED-modules
        octaplayer.lib V7                  5-8-channel-OctaMED-modules
     octamixplayer.lib V7           1-64-channel-OctaMED-Soundstudio-modules


      The source-code is well structured and documentated. Should you be
      interested? You can get it via e-mail or s-mail (but then you have to
      pay for postage and disk!).


@ENDNODE

